# IU X-ray Dataset — Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory analysis of the **Indiana University Chest X-ray Collection (IU X-ray)**, a public dataset of paired chest X-ray images and free-text radiology reports. This is the first stage of a multimodal radiology pipeline combining vision and clinical text for downstream classification and report generation.

---

## Dataset

| Property | Detail |
|---|---|
| Source | Indiana University / NIH Open-i |
| Annotation file | `annotation.json` |
| Splits | `train`, `val`, `test` |
| Total reports | ~3,955 |
| Total images | ~7,470 |
| Image format | PNG (grayscale chest X-rays) |
| Report format | Single free-text string per patient |

**Schema — each entry in `annotation.json`:**

```json
{
  "id": "CXR2384_IM-0942",
  "image_path": ["CXR2384_IM-0942/0.png", "CXR2384_IM-0942/1.png"],
  "report": "The heart size and pulmonary vascularity appear within normal limits ...",
  "split": "train"
}
```

Images are stored under `images/<id>/<index>.png` relative to the dataset root.

---

## Notebook contents

`notebooks/iu_xray_eda.ipynb` — 11 sections:

| # | Section | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Imports and configuration | Sets `DATA_ROOT`, loads libraries |
| 2 | Load and flatten | Reads `annotation.json`, builds a flat DataFrame |
| 3 | Split sizes | Bar chart of train / val / test counts |
| 4 | Images per patient | Distribution of 1 vs 2 vs 3 images per patient |
| 5 | Report completeness | Counts missing or empty report fields |
| 6 | Report text length | Word count and character count distributions |
| 7 | Length by split | KDE overlay comparing report length across splits |
| 8 | Keyword frequency | Word-match counts for 20 clinical finding terms |
| 9 | Top content words | Top 25 words after stopword removal |
| 10 | Sample image preview | Displays 4 example chest X-rays from the train split |
| 11 | Summary and next steps | Key findings and modeling implications |

---

## Setup

```bash
pip install pandas matplotlib seaborn pillow
```

No other dependencies. The notebook uses only standard scientific Python libraries.

---

## Usage

1. Clone or download this repo
2. Open `notebooks/iu_xray_eda.ipynb` in Jupyter
3. Set `DATA_ROOT` in cell 1 to your local dataset path:

```python
DATA_ROOT = Path("/path/to/iu_xray")
```

4. Run All (`Kernel → Restart & Run All`)

Expected directory layout:

```
/path/to/iu_xray/
    annotation.json
    images/
        CXR2384_IM-0942/
            0.png
            1.png
        CXR2926_IM-1328/
            0.png
            ...
```

---

## Key findings

- **No multi-label ground truth.** IU X-ray ships free-text reports only. Labels must be derived via a rule-based labeler (e.g. CheXpert-style) applied to the report text before training a classifier.
- **Most patients have 2 images** (frontal + lateral). A minority have 1 or 3. Train/val/test splits must be done at the patient (`id`) level to avoid data leakage across images from the same patient.
- **Report text is moderately short** (~30–60 words typically), clinically dense, and suitable for a pretrained clinical text encoder such as ClinicalBERT or BioBERT.
- **Class imbalance is significant.** Cardiomegaly, pleural effusion, and "no acute finding" dominate; rarer conditions such as pneumothorax and nodules are infrequent. This will require class-weighted loss or oversampling in downstream training.

---

## Next steps

1. Apply rule-based labeler to report text to produce multi-label targets
2. Build patient-level `Dataset` / `DataLoader` (image + report → label)
3. Train vision-only baseline (ResNet or ViT on X-ray images)
4. Train text-only baseline (ClinicalBERT on report text)
5. Design and train multimodal fusion model (cross-attention or late fusion)

---

## Project context

This EDA notebook is part of a larger multimodal medical imaging research portfolio targeting radiology + clinical text fusion. The full pipeline will combine a vision encoder and a clinical text encoder with a fusion module, trained and evaluated on this dataset.

